==English==
===Etymology===
A reference to the football going up and down the ground by long high kicks.  (Reference: [http://www.anu.edu.au/andc/res/aewords/aewords_ab.php Australian National Dictionary Centre] at the [[w:Australian National University|Australian National University]]).
===Noun===
'''[[aerial]] [[ping pong]]'''
# (''derisive and/or humorous'') [[Australian rules football]].
#: 1965: '' 'Australian Rules draws bigger crowds in Melbourne than Rugby in Sydney.'  'What?' Sydney Sam would say, 'that's not football, mate, it's aerial ping-pong.' '' &mdash; [[w:Frank Hardy|Frank Hardy]], ''The Yarns of Billy Borker'' page 43, quoted in G. A. Wilkes, ''A Dictionary of Australian Colloquialisms'', second edition, 1985, [[w:Sydney University Press|Sydney University Press]], ISBN 0-424-00113-6.
===Usage notes===
Used by supporters of other football codes, usually being people from states of Australia where Australian rules is the dominant code (or, in the past, where it was not played at all).  Fans of Australian rules do not use the term themselves.
